					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Wandering Mages guide</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:jcargile@hotmail.com">Wandering Mage</a> | 
		            5/15/2000 4:05:22 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Hello and welcome to IMO the best class in the game.Lets get started:<BR>
<BR>
I chose to be a erudite because of the high int they start with.  Put 25 points into int and the 5 where you think is best, in my case I put 5 into sta to get a couple extra hp/level.<BR>
<BR>
First thing is to destroy the discord note and give your guild leader his note.  Equip the robe and dagger, scribe your two spells and head into your begining area.  I have read the other guides and some want you to go to other zones to level.  Well more times than not I see 1-5 level individuals running zone to zone to do a corpse retrieval because they weren't ready to enter some of the zones and binding isnt always free.<BR>
<BR>
Before you venture out talk to everyone, even those not belonging to your guild, you may find they have minor quests(clerics/paladins seem to always have a bone quest).  Any xp you get is good xp. I spent 3 hours inquiring within erudin and seeing who sells what and what quests were available before I ventured out.  <BR>
<BR>
When you first get out cast your minor shield(always keep it up), you will see a wide variety of monsters to combat. Fight the ones that con even or less. See if there are any others(level 1-3) who would like to group, xp will be slower than soloing but chances of getting it more often makes up for it.  Levels 1-3 will be the hardest for you, endure it.  Hunt near the guards.  Spell priority is summon food and drink first.  Buy all the spells for each level believe it or not I have found a use for each spell.  Once you start gaining levels you can increase/gain skills, my suggestion is that you put a point in a trade skill(dont do jewelry, alchemy, tinkering, or baking) and save the rest.  Why?  You will get automatic skill points for casting the spells, offense/defense, weapon type come from fighting. You will need these points later on for your research skill and the trade skill will be a source of extra money later on. Turn in quest items as soon as you fill the requirements.  You will get faction increases and access to more quests.  I have found around 60 different quests in erudin.<BR>
<BR>
Ok level 4-7 congrats time to purchase that pet spell, hmm which one? Well unlike necro/enchanter you can summon a pet that best fits your situation.  I like/use them all.  I suggest that earth be your first pet though.  It seems to be the best solo pet for unbuffed mages.  It can root your prey and has the most hp.  So if you get into trouble/run out of mana and you feel you can't win, wait until the prey is rooted and run/gate to guard/zone.  Fire/water is best in groups and air is best against casting mobs.  You can always make another pet so dont be afraid to lose one to save your neck.  Put 1 point into meditate and it will build itself up.  Need money?, well lets see you can summon food, water, daggers(hits wisps and undead), bandages, flashlights(wisps), so sell them.  Ask a higher mage in the area for how much to sell the stuff for. Prices seem to change zone to zone. Some people will tell you that you should just give it to them for free cause they have a 30+ mage/character on another and he always gives stuff out......blah blah etc. So what? that is him, charge for your summoned goods!(unless in a party) you will need the money later on to purchase spells and research items. Dont forget to keep up on your trade skill(s) and save those skill points.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 8-11 I suggest venturing to the next harder location/area.  Purchase your level 12 spells when you get the money and put them in the bank.  By now you have seen all 4 pet types, been grouped, and soloed.  Stick to what bests suits you. Keep saving those skill points.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 12-15 There are big xp/money locations all around norath for characters this level, as an erudin it wasnt hard to figure out where this was. Almost time to spend those skill points.  By now you should start making a profit off your trade skill.     <BR>
<BR>
Levels 16-19 Research time.  3 choices to get pets/some spells, 1)Work with whatever the guild sells(I looked, they all sell the same spells) 2) go to OOT and purchase 16/20 pets spells, or 3)put those saved skill points into research as much as you can and make your pets/spells.<BR>
There are research books and websites to aid you.  Go exploring and find a good area to hunt, for me it was HH, I heard that crush bone was good as well. <BR>
<BR>
Levels 20-23 Specialize in conjuration. Once this skill gets 50 or more put one point into the rest and Dodge. Here I had the easiest time soloing in sk and lake rath. Start trying to procure the items needed for the 24 pets.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 24-28 Thats where I am now(27). There are several good locations to hunt. SK, unrest(if you dont mind dying once in a while), NK, EK, and WC are giving me good solo xp.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 29-?  Well by now you should be able figure out where you want to go with your mage.<BR>
<BR>
Groups; work with different people you will find some are alot better than others. You will find certain classes overpull/underpull prey.  Dont be afraid to leave a group if you feel they are endangering you.  XP at higher levels takes longer to recover and you can lose levels.  Monks and Necros can feign death to stay alive, you cant and sometimes they forget that. If a group cant pull enough prey to justify the time spent say something or excuse yourself and move on. Always bind yourself in a zone next to the one you are hunting in so if you need to gate(always memorized)/zone the mobs forget about you when you re-enter.  Watch how loot is split.  Most fighting classes want free for all split off.  This is because the casters will do most of the sitting to regain the precious mana needed to survive next battle so they will loot the best of the bunch before you will.  So if you want loot/money insist on an order and autosplit on.  Watch out for special drop items.  Make sure everyone one agrees with how it is given out.  Most will do a /ran 100 highest wins.  If you dont one of the losers will cry foul and a re-roll will happen. Sometimes you have a player who is used to playing a different class in your group and will endanger the group by chasing prey into spawns or taking on more than they currently can.  Say something, dont grin and bear it.<BR>
<BR>
Some guides want you to fight guards and townsfolk.  Thats ok if you are already KOS in that area.  My suggestion is DON'T.  Factions in this game is everything. A dark elf who is already KOS in many areas will suggest to kill the high xp guards/townfolk nothing to lose.  You do that and prices go up, if the vendors sell to you.  Guards will attack(after awhile). I found that killing treants (guess who I listened too) (great xp/loot, negative druid/qey faction) was a bad thing once I got back into qeynos. First I was KOS (long corpse retrieval run) then after killing several gnolls/bandits was I able to enter the city, but most vendors wouldn't sell and prices were high and buying low. So watch the faction hits when you kill something.<BR>
<BR>
Soloing: Know the area you are pulling into. Higher levels means the guild sells one or two different pets than you are used to so get used to pulling with each.  Dont depend on SOW, there are times when you just cant get it.  Be willing to pay or trade for breeze, clarity, sow(pet also)when offered. Also watch for KSing, some people feel they own the world and will try to KS you or you may accidently longe range KS someone. So the best bet is to look around the prey (if able)to see if no one is near it. <BR>
<BR>
Well thats it good luck to you.<BR>
<BR>
Wandering Mage<BR>
Haquiem 27th Mage<BR>
Morelle-Thulle
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
